ere are two subsets of size 2 with the same sum. Indeed, the number of pairs is 45 and the number of possible sums for pairs is from 10+11=21 up to 98+99=197, which is 177 possibilities. However, 45 < 177, so we cannot directly apply pigeonhole.\n\n  -- But perhaps we can consider subsets of size up to 2. The total number of nonempty subsets of size up to 2 is 10 + 45 = 55. The possible sums are 10 to 197, which is 188 possibilities. 55 < 188, so no luck.\n\n  -- Next, subsets of size up to 3: 10 + 45 + 120 = 175. Sum of 3 elements: 30 to 297 (but realistically up to 99+98+97=294). 294 - 30 + 1 = 265. 175 < 265.\n\n  -- Next, subsets of size up to 4: 10 + 45 + 120 + 210 = 385. Sum of 4 elements: 40 to 396 (but max is 99+98+97+96=390). 390 - 40 +1 = 351. 385 > 351. Thus, if we consider all nonempty subsets with at most 4 elements, there are 385 subsets and at most 351 possible sums (from 10 to 390), so two of them have the same sum.\n\n  -- How can we use this? We have two subsets A and B with the same sum, and both have at most 4 elements. If they are disjoint, we are done. But if they are not, we can consider A \\ B and B \\ A. \n\n  -- It turns out that if A and B are subsets with |A|, |B| ≤ 4 and sum(A) = sum(B), then A Δ B (symmetric difference) is a set of size at most 8 with sum 0 (mod some number, but we are not using that). \n\n  -- Actually, perhaps we can use the following: if A and B are subsets with sum(A) = sum(B), then A \\ B and B \\ A are two disjoint subsets with sum(A \\ B) - sum(B \\ A) = 0, i.e., sum(A \\ B) = sum(B \\ A).\n\n  -- So we can use this strategy:\n  -- 1. Consider all nonempty subsets of S with at most 4 elements. There are 385 such subsets.\n  -- 2. The possible sums are between 10 and 390 (but max is actually less). \n  -- 3. Since 385 > 351, two subsets have the same sum. Call them A and B.\n  -- 4. Then A \\ B and B \\ A are disjoint with sum(A \\ B) = sum(B \\ A).\n\n  -- But we need to formalize this in Lean, and there are some